text: The Biblical account of the ten plagues is quite detailed. It describes the pollution of the water supply, and devastation of the livestock and vegetation of the land. The Israelites left, depriving the land of its slave labor, and they carried away much of the land's wealth in the form of silver, gold, and clothing (Exodus 12:36). Also, the army and the Pharaoh were drowned in the "Red Sea," leaving the country with weakened defenses. The Exodus must surely have left a bold signature in Egyptian history. What do the historians find following the reign of Pepy II's successor?  Pepy II's successor was the final Pharaoh of the Old Kingdom of Egypt. Grimal says: "The Old Kingdom ended with a period of great confusion." (page 89). Summarizing an ancient Egyptian literary/historical work called Admonitions, which comments on Egypt following the reign of Pepy II's successor, Grimal says:  It was the collapse of the whole society, and Egypt itself had become a world in turmoil, exposed to the horrors of chaos which was always waiting for the moment when the personification of the divine being - the Pharaoh - neglected his duties or simply disappeared. (Grimal, page 138) This time period was characterized by famine, an expected result of the plagues described in the book of Exodus. This famine was limited to the Nile valley (Grimal, page 139)---as the Bible's narrative would lead one to expect. There was anarchy and a struggle for political power. Egypt's foreign trade ceased and Egyptian mining in the Sinai peninsula "also seems to have been abandoned" (Grimal, page 139). The nation of Egypt had obviously suffered a severe blow---as one would expect from what the Bible tells us of the events accompanying the Exodus.
author: CmPunkBeast

text: Egypt = Gopt, Gupt, Gupta = "Protector," like a, "Father" (Sanskrit)  Agade = Aga, De, Deios, Dios, Deus = "Crowned," "God" as "The Father" or place of the Father's coronation as King of Mesopotamia. (Celtic) + (Sumerian)  Aegyptus = "Aegis" and "Pt" or "Ptah" which is, "Pater" as in, "Sign of the Father." (Greco-Phoenician)  "Sargon," was the first, "King of the Four Quarters," of the world; Nimrod/Uranus/Acmon  Anyone who reads about it can see the Bible is a later combination of a series of tales dealing with Sargon, not the, "Sargon" of Akkad and Persia but the first, "Sargon." The one who's name means literally, "Dragon," in ancient Sumerian, Celtic and Sanskrit. The Greeks admitted that they created new forms of mythologies from word-plays, transliterations, mistranslations and double-meanings or metaphors.  Over time this technique forms the legend.

text: First things first. The Hebrew Moses, Christian Moses and Islamic Moses are all the same. The first text to ever mention the name Moses was the Old testament. Ask any christian or muslim if they believe in the divinity of the Old Testament and they will admit, yes. So Moses was the same for all three religions, although of course, Judaism is the only legitimate religion. Everything that follows was created by one man which can never be proven for obvious reasons and is bologna.   Second, although all sacred texts in the Old Testament mentioned only the name Pharaoh, there is obviously a name associated with each pharaoh. However, the Torah does not explicitly mention which pharaoh it was during the exodus. There were scientific studies done by archeologists and they linked Moses' time to the Pharaoh Ramses. But whether or not those things actually happened in that manner of fashion, or at all, is not the case. Ridley Scott just wanted to take the story of Moses from the bible and put it to the big screen without diverting from the stuff in the bible.

text: First, I'll start with the obvious thing: The story of the Exodus is a part of MY, a Hebrew, national mythology. It is my. Associating it to Christian dogma, western society is CULTURAL APPROPRIATION.  Second, the movie has a butch of historical inaccuracies: 1. Plate-armors did not exist in Egypt in the time of Ramesses II. 2. The trailer says that there are "400 thousand slaves". The bible says there were 600,000 Israelite MEN. If we add the women, it makes around 1.2 million. If we add at least 1 child per-family, it's almost 2 million people. Out of the around 2.5 million population of Egypt at the time, it's morbidly illogical to assume it happened, but let's not get into it. 3. The banners depicted in the trailer, as Egyptian flags of some sort - did not exist. Vexillology and banners appeared only during Roman times, when the Legions of Rome had their own banners - that's around 400 years after the time of Ramesses. 4. Just an anecdote: The name of Moses and Ramesses come from the same word: Messy, or Messe. "Ramesses" (or in Egyptian, "Ra3 Messe") means "Child of Ra [the son god]". Moses simply means "Child".

text: This film is against Israel, complete with deliberate errors. Ramesses 11 was not the Pharaoh of the Exodus, neither was the Biblical Pharaoh killed in the Exodus. Research reveals that Thutmose 111 was the Pharaoh. Historical knowledge debunks the theory and this script which both claim the exodus was caused by the 16th century BCE Santorini tsunami blast, the dates do not match up. Thutmoses 111 reigned 1479–1425 BC in the 18th Dynasty. Ramesses 11 reigned 1279–1213 BC in the 19th Dynasty. The name of Moses has its origins from Thutmose, not Ramesses.    Beware of this movie, it might be a good movie, but it is not accurate history and Moses will be portrayed as a bit of a psychopath.

text: Regardless of belief, I find it fascinating that there is no real debate about the validity of men such as Caesar, Homer, Napoleon, etc. True, we have historical evidence to support them--as do we for the Bible's historical authenticity. However, in all the world, there has been no single topic that has sparked such wide-ranging and heated debate as the Bible, as the concept of God, Jesus, etc. Interesting that countless people (atheists included…who tout tolerance) have no problem when someone says they are Buddhist or Hindu, etc…but when a Christian protests the removal of God from a Biblical account on the basis that it cheapens the story, there is great protest. In the very least, it would appear that the atheist, railing against the claims of Christianity, or the agnostic or whomever, is shaken somewhere in the  core of his being so that he must feel the need to respond. In short, it is interesting that throughout history, "God" has produced such an effect on man, has evoked such a response. In terms of personal belief: if Jesus was not who he claimed to be and Christians believed in a great lie that taught salvation and goodness and love to all men, then they lose nothing. If Jesus was who he said he was (the Son of God) and people believe him…then they gain everything and still lose nothing. If Jesus was who he said he was and a man chooses not to believe him, then that man gains nothing and loses everything. Furthermore, Jesus could only be one of three things: Lord, Liar, or Lunatic. He was not just a good moral teacher…he claimed to be God. No other option. If he was deliberately deceiving his followers by saying he was God, then he was a liar…but this negates his teachings about honesty. A hypocrite. But this goes counter to the effect his teachings have had on humanity in general (true, some have twisted his words for personal gain, violence, etc. That is a horrible travesty.) In general, however, people have been changed for the good. Jesus preached about moral purity, dignity, displayed through his life's work. Historian Philip Schaff gives this argument: "How, in the name of logic, common sense, and experience, could an imposter have invented, and consistently maintained from beginning to end, the purest and noblest character known in history with the most perfect air of truth and reality. How could he have conceived and successfully carried out a plan of unparalleled beneficence, moral magnitude, and sublimity, and sacrificed his own life for it, in the face of the strongest prejudices of his people and age?" He could not have been a liar and convinced people to believe in that lie for thousands of years…the lie would have imploded by now. Now, it is possible that he was a lunatic. A crazy man who convinced himself of his divinity and started proclaiming that divinity with full conviction to the people of Israel. Jesus believing himself to be God sounds like a person today, myself for example, believe myself to be JFK in the flesh, or Elvis, or an alien from Mars. I would be deluded and possibly even locked up so I would be a menace to anyone else as I wander North America touting my beliefs. However, let's say Jesus was schizo…A schizophrenic person typically desires to escape the world of reality…Claiming to be God would definitely be a retreat from reality. But in light of all we know (granted we actually read the Biblical account, historical texts supporting his life, etc.) about Jesus, it's hard to fathom he was mentally deranged. He spoke some of the most incredibly profound things ever said. "Do unto others as you would have them do to you." (The Golden Rule, just to mention one.) When you consider the depth and skillfulness of Jesus' teachings, they smack of total mental soundness. His Sermon on the Mount has more practical psychology in it than the writings of Freud, Jung, and others put together…Regardless of whether you believe his claims to be God, if you but read his teachings, they are the perfect blueprint for a successful life and true contentment. My question, objectively, remains: "how could a complete lunatic maintain perfect clarity and possess such a razor-sharp intellect as the teachings of Jesus seem to suggest?" True, a schizophrenic man may possess unsurpassed musical genius or even mental genius (The Soloist, excellent movie and story)…but I have yet to hear of a schizophrenic or any other person that we label "handicapped" uttering words that have changed lives and nations. It is difficult for us to dismiss Jesus as an utter lunatic with delusions of grandeur. I must personally conclude that He was who he actually claimed to be. Jesus Christ, Son of God. Now, we could ask ourselves all these questions: Lunatic? Liar? Lord? and say "No!" to all three. That is a choice that one must live with. The evidence, logically speaking, points to the validity of his claims. The question is not: possible? It's what is probable? We can't bench the Jesus question. There has to be a choice, and there has to be a living with the consequences of that choice. Seems like most Christians (look at the middle east) are choosing "Lord," and living with great suffering…But you never hear of them renouncing that belief (unless they were never serious about it in the first place.) Christians in America get labelled "intolerant"…but before we can call them such, mustn't we ask ourselves: "By calling a Christian intolerant, am I not being intolerant myself?" Two-way street. Who you decide Jesus is and was must be your choice. Granted, the evidence seems to support the validity of his claims, but one might choose to deny that because of the significant moral implications a belief in him would have. So, I guess I encourage all people: Christians, atheists, moralists, Muslims, Buddhists, Hindus, etc. to continue to seek out truth wherever it may be found. Though I may say "Jesus", continue seeking for yourself. I encourage Christians not to respond with rage when an atheist brings up a good point. Similarly I encourage atheists not to respond with disgust and intolerance when a Christian (informed or otherwise) states their belief. Ultimately all of us have faith: the atheist that there is no God, the Christian that there is a God.

text: Judging from the trailer, I don't think there's going to be a lot of "I was once his brother" moments, which kind of ruins the whole thing for me. It kind of sets it up too much so that there's ONE central "bad guy" and ONE central "good guy."  I don't like that.  I want to see Moses, devastated on the inside, because he's essentially ruining his brother's life. The same brother he grew up and played with. I want to see Ramses, torturing himself over the decision to slay his own brother or defend his own people. I think The Prince of Egypt portrayed that very well, and that was a pretty good movie.  But then again, the director DOES have a right to make the movie how he sees fit. If Ridley Scott wanted to direct this movie a certain way, then it's absolutely possible that he could make a good film regardless of the direction he takes it in.   So I'm not saying this is going to be a BAD movie. It's got Ridley Scott and Christian Bale and Sigourney Weaver, so it's got a lot of star power, but at the same time, they're adapting a Bible story, which is traditionally a very violent and explicit story, and making it PG-13, and I don't know if that's the right direction to be taking.  But that feels unfair. I think the only way to see how this turns out is by waiting and watching it just like everyone else.

text: The ignorance of some of the comments here is staggering. First of all, Egypt was, by and large, a heterogeneous society. But the ancient Egyptians did make a distinction between themselves and the people who lived further south, in what was called Nubia. It is now Sudan. You can see this distinction in their tomb paintings and other historical records. There are actually more pyramids in Nubia than there are in Egypt, and the Nubians built quite a civilization of their own, albeit one heavily influenced by the culture of ancient Egypt. At one point in history, Nubia actually conquered Egypt and a number of black pharaohs reigned, including one named Taharqa, whose pylon can still be seen in the ruins of ancient Thebes. But all you have to do is look at the historical record to SEE that while there were certainly black men and women living in ancient Egypt, all the ancient Egyptians weren't black. There are mummies with blond wavy hair still attached to their heads. Take a look at the mummy of Rameses II, the pharaoh depicted in "Gods and Kings," which is on display at the Cairo Museum. One look and you can see he wasn't black! If you want to get all upset over historical inaccuracies, an Egyptian prince such as Moses would not have worn a goatee as Bale does in the early scenes of the film. He would have been clean shaven.

That doesn't mean we must accept white supremacist propaganda as truth.  The Ancient Egyptians were African.  The Ancient Egyptian language is an African language (not a Semitic one).  The people would have looked much like the rest of the nile valley populations of East and North East Africa, not like Danes.  Obviously from painted reliefs, sculptures and written descriptions of the population of Ancient Egypt the people were primarily but not exclusively Black.  Also, the farther north you travel in the county the "less Black" the people become because of the natural intermixing of populations.  Nowhere in paintings or sculptures have I ever seen a person, supposedly of a native Egyptian during the Pharaonic period who looks like Christian Bale.  If any of you know of such please direct me to that sculpture/painting.

text: I am going to be so happy when they start to represent Biblical characters as they were.  People are mad about Black Annie, about the Black storm trooper in Star Wars but not about the inaccuracies in Biblical movies placed in Africa. Let's face it the English European Whites weren't there.  Even Greeks weren't there.  And although you may hate it even the Arabians were not there in the bountiful numbers they are today. For those of you who say blacks should not be in fairy tales made from Europe, I say Whites should not be in nonfiction epics based in Africa.  And before the storm of idiot replies I expect to receive telling me that Egypt wasn't Black let me quote past Greek historians who were in Egypt after the year BC.  "Herodotus states in a few passages that the Egyptians were black/dark. According to most translations, Herodotus states that a Greek oracle was known to be from Egypt because she was "black", that the natives of the Nile region are "black with heat", and that Egyptians were "black skinned with woolly hair". Lucian observes an Egyptian boy and notices that he is not merely black, but has thick lips. Diodorus Siculus mentioned that the Aethiopians considered the Egyptians a colony. Appollodorus, a Greek, calls Egypt the country of the black footed ones."  These historians ought to know they were there and not the so called people who want to change history just to feel superior.

text: People in the comments are so ignorant, and I'm starting to think modern day Egyptians are delusional. This all stems from the unfortunate idea that all black people look the same. Yes, Egyptians now definitely look more caucasian due to migration and changes over time. But there's no denying Ancient Egyptians had a large variety of appearances. They weren't all black. but they also weren't all olive skinned. You can see this in their own artwork and in writings. Nubians are a group of people in ancient egypt that are often depicted and they are consistently described as being extremely dark in complexion. Ancient Egypt spanned over many generations and their artwork depicts them as looking more black or more semitic closer to the first century and depending on the dynasty of the time. But there's no mistaking that none of them were European looking in the slightest. Even Cleopatra, while not black was Greek of the ptolemy group. Greeks were also not white by todays standards. Greeks admired blond hair and blue eyes which were rare features among their people and they depicted their gods as having these features, but they actually didn't look like that and any historian will tell you that. All reconstructions and sculptures of Nefertiti show her to look what like what would considered to be black in America today. I would compare her features to somalians or the model Iman, definitely not a European looking woman in the slightest. The truth is that middle eastern/egyptian people love to seperate themselves from blacks but there's a very fine line between the races in some regions and at the end of the day they weren't treated much better by Europeans. You are all inhabitants of the same continent and the truth is that some mixing happened over time because intersectionality often exists in race. You can be white hispanic, or black hispanic but if you're light skinned and you're from mexico it doesn't make you european. We see this intersectionality a lot in places like Brazil and the West Indies, where we have people who look Indian but are very much mixed with blacks and the West Africans slaves that were bought over by colonizers at the time. Even if we keep all the race things aside, this movie is still a mess since it's a biblical story. Moses's wife was described in the Bible as being a very dark woman, so much so that Miriam did not like her. For that God cursed her with leprosy and Moses had to pray for her forgiveness. So, it's not only historically innacurate but it also whitewashes the story it's based on. I mean honestly, Christian Bale as Moses? He's English. He does not have origins anywhere near Africa and he is not olive in complexion in the slightest. Same goes for pretty much for the rest of this cast. It's entirely made up of british and european people. You wouldn't make a movie about medieval europe with an all middle eastern cast so why would you do this with a movie about Ancient Egypt and the hebrew population. See Prince of Egypt for a better depiction. That film shows the range of black and browm people that would have been a more accurate depiction.

text: To debate whether Egyptians were "black" or "white" is idiotic because those are modern social political terms.  Their is somewhat a shared ancestral history out of Africa bound together by the y dna E1b  that came from the East Africa and spread North, South and into the Mediterranean.  Modern Egypt is the results of  eons of invasions by the Persians, Nubians and later Greeks finally Turks that lasted 600 years. Nubians and Ancient Egyptians were always at war.  Eventually Nubians conquered Egypt but only held it for 100 years then the Persians.  Ancient Egyptians were more of a Oromo, Beja, Amazigh Berber mix not Arab.  Europeans like Iberian Celts, Irish, and pre Briton Picts were living in mud huts ( a la "Brave Heart" but earlier)  and were more tribal at this time.

text: I really admire those in this comment section who do the diligence but are also respectful in sharing their viewpoints on a profound topic. I am a believer in God, this only means something when I also value intelligence (a healthy dose of open-mindedness seems crucial) and love better known as harmony across the planet. If (G)od were to actually arbitrate powers as proof, (like showing answers to a test), what would be the obvious implications. Where would humans' interests for research or imagination as necessary forms for ambition and desire to reach our fullest potentials go? Better yet, how are we to truly learn anything of a divine worth if god always intervened directly with our living experiences? I think that this would be as trivial as the movie on a larger scale. At worse, what do you think the human condition would be like if we were in the presence of something unbelievable? We'd all likely become schizophrenics if most of us haven't become absolutely psychotic already because of the extreme makeup of a rationalist society today. Irrationality doesn't make something fictional or fantasy, that's art which is the closest universal language for speaking to one's soul, spirit, or state of impressionism. Irrationality is merely a word charged as being something negative. But I would argue that irrationality is supreme quality of reasoning to an otherwise universe of contradictory truths, unpredictability, and surprises.   By the way, freedom at a absolute level of its implication would seem to leave us totally in the dark to ignorance (uncertainties) until we began to collectively yet freely coexist in a loving planetary playground filled with sharing each others' opinions/ experience. I would argue that like the apparent subtle impossible possibility of the Big Bang notion, one seemingly improbable potentially significant mere human being on this planet today has what it takes to change reality by simply being real with themselves and then sharing that to open-minded yet critically curious individuals.   For faithful peeps, I'd kindly encourage to consider the idea that we are not perfect but perfect just as we are. This should hopefully remind some of us to be patient with those who sincerely hold true to their orientations to what's true as much as we do in our faiths.     For those not so easily swayed, a friendly quote to spark healthier consideration about anomalies, uncertainties, or questions not yet solved (mysteries). "Coincidences are god's way of remaining anonymous" Albert Einstein. if (G)od were to show its complete presence, we would in all likelihood not be conscious in the common sense of the word I suspect. Perhaps atheism is sort of like an extremely narrow outlook onto facts as vast as most of the size of the universe. My premise for a rhetorical argument is that how does one maintain a convincing idea that we are the only ones in the universe? Whether we are or not, I'm sure just the basis of the question raises profound implications for seriously intriguing general public discussion.

text: What actually bothers me about this is not only did they cast white people but the movie’s historical inaccuracies are too many to ignore, including the film’s depiction of Jews as having built the Pyramids, and that an earthquake, not a miracle by Moses, caused the Red Sea to part. the movie does not align with the biblical myth. All of the 138 pyramids known to us were built during the Old Kingdom and the Middle Kingdom, that is between 2686 B.C.E. and 1650 B.C.E. But the Exodus, if it indeed did take place, has been dated to some time between the 15th and the 12th centuries B.C.E. That means the pyramids would have been completed long before the putative Jewish enslavement in Egypt. Where does this idea that Jews in Egyptian captivity toiled on the construction of the pyramids come from? That is not clear, but it certainly is not from the Bible. if they are going to make a biblical movie, then why not make it historically accurate? it just dumb. They should have called this movie 'fictional superheros'.

text: This genre obviously appeals to religious audiences (myself included), who will undoubtedly gauge the film with Scriptural text and make comparisons. It would be naïve to think otherwise. The common pitfall for directors--with respect to religious material--is to provide the viewer with rational, scientific explanations for all of the SUPERNATURAL PHENOMENONS that occurred in the Scripture. For example:  1. In 'Exodus: Gods & Kings', Ridley Scott portrays a carnivorous crocodile frenzy to rationalize the Nile turning red with blood; whereas in the actual Book of Exodus, Aaron’s staff was placed into the river and this of itself caused the waters to turn. 2. The interpretation was introduced of a ‘low-tide’ Red Sea, essentially making it more scientifically believable, convenient, with perfect timing for thousands of Hebrews to cross over...during this "low-tide"...at the very time Ramses’ army was hunting them down.

Voici ce que dit le texte biblique: "Aaron leva la verge, et il frappa les eaux qui étaient dans le fleuve, sous les yeux de Pharaon et sous les yeux de ses serviteurs ; et toutes les eaux du fleuve furent changées en sang". Je vous déconseille d'acheter ce film et de gaspiller votre argent pour rien. Exode 7:14-25 L'Éternel dit à Moïse : Pharaon a le coeur endurci ; il refuse de laisser aller le peuple. Va vers Pharaon dès le matin ; il sortira pour aller près de l'eau, et tu te présenteras devant lui au bord du fleuve. Tu prendras à ta main la verge qui a été changée en serpent, et tu diras à Pharaon : L'Éternel, le Dieu des Hébreux, m'a envoyé auprès de toi, pour te dire : Laisse aller mon peuple, afin qu'il me serve dans le désert. Et voici, jusqu'à présent tu n'as point écouté. Ainsi parle l'Éternel : A ceci tu connaîtras que je suis l'Éternel. Je vais frapper les eaux du fleuve avec la verge qui est dans ma main ; et elles seront changées en sang. Les poissons qui sont dans le fleuve périront, le fleuve se corrompra, et les Égyptiens s'efforceront en vain de boire l'eau du fleuve. L'Éternel dit à Moïse : Dis à Aaron : Prends ta verge, et étends ta main sur les eaux des Égyptiens, sur leurs rivières, sur leurs ruisseaux, sur leurs étangs, et sur tous leurs amas d'eaux. Elles deviendront du sang : et il y aura du sang dans tout le pays d'Égypte, dans les vases de bois et dans les vases de pierre. Moïse et Aaron firent ce que l'Éternel avait ordonné. Aaron leva la verge, et il frappa les eaux qui étaient dans le fleuve, sous les yeux de Pharaon et sous les yeux de ses serviteurs ; et toutes les eaux du fleuve furent changées en sang. Les poissons qui étaient dans le fleuve périrent, le fleuve se corrompit, les Égyptiens ne pouvaient plus boire l'eau du fleuve, et il y eut du sang dans tout le pays d'Égypte. Mais les magiciens d'Égypte en firent autant par leurs enchantements. Le coeur de Pharaon s'endurcit, et il n'écouta point Moïse et Aaron, selon ce que l'Éternel avait dit. Pharaon s'en retourna, et alla dans sa maison ; et il ne prit pas même à coeur ces choses. Tous les Égyptiens creusèrent aux environs du fleuve, pour trouver de l'eau à boire ; car ils ne pouvaient boire de l'eau du fleuve. Il s'écoula sept jours, après que l'Éternel eut frappé le fleuve.

text: Its supposed to be a story about Moses and God's deliverance for the Hebrews to set them free from the bondage and slavery by Egyptians. I bought this movie because I saw the trailer and I thought it was good biblical movie because I saw the ten plagues. But I was wrong, when I watched it, I saw that its another wanna be christian movie that doesn't show the true essence of the biblical true story that is from the Bible.   There was part of the scene in the movie that showed the burning bush and I was really disappointed because thats the part where God talked to Moses and Moses was reverent in the presence of God, where God also told Moses to remove the sandals from his feet because he was standing on a Holy ground. But they made God into a child in that scene and didn't even have the biblical dialogue between God and  Moses. They changed it and made up their own conversation.   They also failed to reach the acceptable biblical character of Moses in that movie. They have made him irreverent towards God, there were scenes that Moses yelled at God blaming Him for taking him away from his family. When the truth was, God didn't take Moses away from his wife, his wife journeyed with him to Egypt when he was chosen to lead the Hebrews freedom from slavery and out of Egypt. I was so disappointed with how they made Moses in that movie. He was supposed to be the most humblest man in the face of the earth, and didn't use weapons and force against Pharoah but a simple Rod in his hands glorifying the power of God, sending plagues in Egypt. But in that movie, Moses didn't even have the Rod, and that was my favorite thing about Moses.  They also made God look bad in that movie, depicting as a killer. Pharaoh said in that movie " What kind of God that kills? who worships this kind of God?" After the plagues and the first borns lives where taken away. First of all, God is Judge and He gives life, and He has the right to take it away what belongs to Him. Nothing belongs to us. Our lives are borrowed from God. He gives, but when He takes away, May His Name be Praised! Because everything in Heaven and on earth belongs to HIM! So he has the right to Judge Egypt and after all, the Pharaoh was stubborn and didn't take heed to let God's people go. He made God his enemy and who can win against God? No one.  All in all, I was excited to watch the movie and paid for it  because I thought that this movie had a great opportunity to glorify God with its special effects during the scenes of  ten plagues. But Hollywood ruined the true biblical story in that movie. What a waste! That movie had the opportunity to Glorify God with its special effects  and spread the message across towards people, but they ruined it. There were a lot of scenes in that movie that was false in the essence of biblical truth in nature. "The Ten Commandments" and "Prince Of Egypt" were far batter.

text: Scientists have extracted and analyzed DNA from mummies that are thousands of years old, and they have found that the ancient Egyptians are actually more genetically similar to people living today in the Near East — countries like Israel, Lebanon, and Syria — than modern-day Egyptians. The team then compared the ancient mummy DNA to the DNA of both ancient and modern people in the same region. It turns out that, on a genetic level, the ancient Egyptians aren’t so different from modern people living in the Near East. In fact, they have more in common with those in the Near East than today’s Egyptians. For example, the mummies didn’t have any DNA from sub-Saharan Africa, whereas about 20 percent of today’s Egyptians have sub-Saharan genes. Study lead author Johannes Krause told Science that the modern-day variation might be because either the spread of Islam or more trade increased contact between the different parts of Africa.

text: A brilliant film depicting the archetypal prophetic struggle between loyalty to one’s people, and the allegiance to the wishes of God. Bale did a fantastic job at humanising the most influential Prophet of the Old Testament, reflecting the father, law bearer, Prince and warrior in a fully formed compelling character. Criticism toward the film is based on the fact that it does not follow the Old Testament. But it is virtually an impossible task to adapt the Biblical events to film. Scott has taken the wise approach of understanding Moses from a literary perspective, as opposed to a purely theological one. Masterclass of a film👌🏻👌🏻.
